Ask HN: As an indie developer, how can you fight fraud?
text:
I'm the developer of Rectangle [1], a FOSS window manager for macOS, and its paid version, Rectangle Pro.

This past year, someone created a fraudulent site[2] that has gained enough traction to rank on the first page of Google search results for my official site. Users have started falling for the scam, and are buying a cracked version of my paid app.

It would appear that my only recourse is to report the fraudulent site and associated accounts to each of their services (registrar, Google Safebrowsing, etc), which I have done. Unfortunately, there is no result from this, and I've started to try to get my users to also report it [3].

Is there anything else I can do? Does anyone else have a similar experience where they were successful?

[1] https://rectangleapp.com [2] rectanglemac(dot)com [3] https://github.com/rxhanson/Rectangle/discussions/969

Do I have enough experience for Google senior Eng?
text:
I got an interview at Google - it’s a company most people dream of working at, so why am I writing this instead of grinding leetcode ?

Well it’s for a senior Eng role. Do I actually have enough experience or will I waste my time grinding leetcode just to be told off.

So, my experience: - 1 year of no name company internship - masters (with published research) - 2 years at startup - 1 year at Amazon as L4 ( on resume just says software dev so level is not explicit) - parents related to my work at startup

I did not apply to the position, I was contacted about it by a recruiter. Do they have a decent screening process before the interview invitation?

I am just worried the recruiter is impressed by my skills, but when I talk to an engineer they will tell me to stop wasting their time.

Impostor syndrome or reasonable concern ?
